How cliche, I am reviewing Gary Danko and giving it five stars...duh! I will start with the highlight of my experience, which was Seamus, our waiter. Seamus' high level of customer service exceeded my expectations, and his personal touch is what made my birthday dinner phenomenal. Seamus wasn't just nice and attentive, he was such a gentleman and at no point did he seem condescending, boring, or stuffy. The one thing I was disappointed by had nothing to do with the food or the staff. I was so excited to get dressed up and eat at GD, but upon walking in there were people in jeans and sweatshirts. Not a sweater, but a gray cotton sweatshirt like the kind you were given as a PE uniform in high school. Yeah yeah yeah, I know, clothes don't make a person, blah blah blah, but man, it sure doesn't hurt to at least throw on a button down collared shirt and some khakis! Besides, Gary Danko is special (because I said so), and on their website it says formal attiure requested. If I invited someone to my party and said formal attire requested, I'd stop them at the door if they looked like the rolled in off the street. Kidding! Anyway, I guess this is good news for people who like to dress "comfortably" or those who can't be bothered to buy a dress shirt or a dress. I was pleased with my choices from the menu. I went with the five course meal and started with the Dungeness Crab Risotto. For being an appetizer, the portion is quite large and it's heavy but delicious. There were large heaping chunks of lobster and shrimp in the risotto. My dinner date had the Dungeness Crab Salad which would probably be an excellent choice for someone with a small appetite. The salad was beautifully plated and tasty. My second course consisted of the Seared Sea Scallops which weren't over the top amazing, but the scallops were cooked perfectly and the leeks and mushrooms they were served with were a nice acompaniment. I will try something different from the fish and seafood category next time. I originally was going to skip the meat and game bird course because I didn't see anything that sounded amazing but decided at the last minute to indulge myself. I selected the Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, and I am SO happy I did! The meat was tender, sliced to the thickness that I like, and the seasoning was spot-on. This entree was so delectable, I would order it again. The cheese experience needs its own paragraph because it was epic. Seamus rolled the cheese cart over to our table and asked if there was anything we didn't like about cheese. We answered no, and he began telling us about each cheese, whether it was bold or mild, what the rhine was made of, what type of milk the cheese was made from, and where it was from. I LOVE CHEESE!! I selected my three cheese and my dinner date selected three different ones. Perhaps because it was my birthday or because I had been chatting with him throughout dinner, Seamus ran to the back after serving our cheese and appeared with two lovely bottles of port. Seamus suggested we try the ports with the blue cheese we selected, and of course it was a great idea. I could tasted the caramel in my glass. I asked Seamus about the cheeses that I liked and he was able to tell me where I can find some of them locally. Dessert: Strawberry-Rhubarb Tart. I normally like dense, sweet desserts but decided to try something different. I can be succinct and write that I ate the whole tart. I was then presented with a lemon mousse with a birthday candle in it which took me five attempts to blow out. I was beyond full at this point so I took my little birthday dessert to go. I was also given a banana breakfast cake wrapped in a pretty bag to have with my morning coffee. In sum, Gary Danko is awesome. You don't have to dress nice to eat here, but I do know the staff appreciates the effort, as do I. When I return to Gary Danko in the near future, I'm going to request Seamus as my waiter.

Of course, you can't give less than 5 stars to such an establishment. I am not going to give a detailed review of the food we had. Other Yelpers have done plenty of that, and I am sure they change the menu often. So here are the highlights. 1. Preparing this only a week before, it was impossible to get a reservation that was not super early or super late. We opted for 5.30pm and if you want to go at a more decent supper time, plan ahead... way ahead. 2. We had the 5 course menu though, so we were glad for the 5.30pm reservation since we spent 3 hours and a half there. I was extremely surprised by the amount of food they give you. I expected tiny portions but I could not even touch the 5th course (dessert) because I was so full. Also, know that if you tell them it's for a special occasion (it was my birthday) they will give you a delicious little cake, so you can plan your course sans dessert. 3. Another reason why I was so full is that the food is extremely rich. We tried a little bit of everything with our 10 courses, and although the food is excellent of course, I must admit I was not "wowed" as I expected. As a comparison, the food at Masa's impressed me more. 4. Service was perfect, though it was a little slow. I understand they probably tried to give us some time between each course because of the quantity of food, but we waited so much at times that we got almost bored. 5. Ambiance/decor: very classy of course, but with a touch of casualness I appreciated. For the same comparison, I felt a bit more at ease than at the more "stuck up" Masa's. Final thought: great restaurant, will definitely go back. I also thought it was quite inexpensive for what such a place. You can easily go for the 3-course + a glass of wine, which I am sure will leave you full, for less than $100!

Amazing. The food, the ambiance, the service, simply amazing. Boyfriend & I came here for our Two Years & Six Months anniversary, just as an excuse to try this place out. We got four courses each and everything was just ... scrumptious. Mine: -The Foie Gras was seared to perfection & melted in my mouth. -The roast maine lobster with potato puree was cooked to perfection. The lobster wasn't rubbery and the seasoning was just right. I originally had my doubts about potato puree, but I found myself wanting an entire bowl of it. -The loin of lamb was disappointing. The slices were cut so thin that I didn't feel like I was getting my money's worth. It didn't have much lamb flavor to it either. In fact, all I could taste was the sauce that the lamb was dipped in. And where was the mint yogurt? The only sauces I found on my plate was hummus and the eggplant stew. -The trio Creme Brulee flavors I got were Bourben, Vanilla & Nutella. Vanilla was my favorite. Distinct vanilla flavor without it being overly sweet. Boyfriend: -I'm not a fan of cooked oysters, so the Oyster & Caviar wasn't all that great for me. -Coconut Thai Curry was pretty good. I was surprised my boyfriend liked it, or even ordered it since he's not a fan of coconut. But he absolutely loved this dish. -The seared filet of beef was good. From the bite I had though, the meat seemed to be tougher than i expected it to be. -The chocolate souflee was light and fluffy... It felt like a cloud melting in your mouth. The waiters were extremely polite. I thought we'd be discriminated against since we were so much younger than everybody else there, but we were still treated with respect & I appreciated that a lot. I didn't get full off of the courses though, I ate every single thing off the plate and left glad that I came half hungry and that they had complimentary bread. Maybe our portions were smaller since we ordered four courses? All in all, this place is a great place for a date. Definitely fancier & pricier than the places I'm used to going to as a poor college student. But I'd definitely come back again for a special day.

I have been wanting to go here fora while and finally had the chance when I decided to take my fiance here for his 35th birthday. It lived up the hype, which I think is hard to do! I think what really sets this place apart from other nice restaurants is the level of service. The service was brilliant - they were timely, knowledgeable AND they were nice. I cannot stress that last point enough. I have been to some excellent restaurants where the servers were good at their jobs but snooty. You kind of expect that from high-end restaurants but I have to say that I really prefer the approachable and friendly tact that this restaurant has taken. I actually liked the atmosphere of the place - muted but soothing decor and the fresh flowers we had near our seat kept giving me some beautiful smells to savor in between meals. We were seated in an intimate corner booth for two, which was perfect for the special occasion (also great for people watching). The food was also notable, as you'd expect. I really appreciate the flexibility in the menu. I decided to do a five course meal consisting of 2 apps, 1 seafood dish, a meat dish, and a dessert. They'll adjust the size of each dish regardless of whether it's an app or an entree to make sure you're full by the end - and that definitely seemed to work for me! I was fully satiated by the end. I had the fried egg and polenta dish first, which I thought was just delicious. I followed that with the lobster risotto, which was also a big win. Both of these were hearty and had a nice blend of different flavors and textures. I then moved to a coconut seafood curry - that was interesting. It was probably my least favorite dish, although I think most people would probably like it. I just happen to be one of those darn Americans who likes their thai-style food to taste like cheap thai restaurants make it. :-P My meat course was buffalo, which I thought was excellently prepared and tasted very nice. I ended the meal with a selection of sorbets, which I really loved for their flavor - the passion fruit was my particular favorite. I'll let my fiance write his own review of his meal if he would like, but I think it's safe to say we both came away very satisfied with the experience, and we would definitely value a return trip.

    Of course, you can't give less than 5 stars to such an establishment.

    I am not going to give a detailed review of the food we had. Other Yelpers have done plenty of that, and I am sure they change the menu often.

    So here are the highlights.
    1. Preparing this only a week before, it was impossible to get a reservation that was not super early or super late. We opted for 5.30pm and if you want to go at a more decent supper time, plan ahead... way ahead.

    2. We had the 5 course menu though, so we were glad for the 5.30pm reservation since we spent 3 hours and a half there.
    I was extremely surprised by the amount of food they give you. I expected tiny portions but I could not even touch the 5th course (dessert) because I was so full. Also, know that if you tell them it's for a special occasion (it was my birthday) they will give you a delicious little cake, so you can plan your course sans dessert.

    3. Another reason why I was so full is that the food is extremely rich. We tried a little bit of everything with our 10 courses, and although the food is excellent of course, I must admit I was not "wowed" as I expected. As a comparison, the food at Masa's impressed me more.

    4. Service was perfect, though it was a little slow. I understand they probably tried to give us some time between each course because of the quantity of food, but we waited so much at times that we got almost bored.

    5. Ambiance/decor: very classy of course, but with a touch of casualness I appreciated. For the same comparison, I felt a bit more at ease than at the more "stuck up" Masa's.

    Final thought: great restaurant, will definitely go back. I also thought it was quite inexpensive for what such a place. You can easily go for the 3-course + a glass of wine, which I am sure will leave you full, for less than $100!

    Mine:
    -The Foie Gras was seared to perfection & melted in my mouth.
    -The roast maine lobster with potato puree was cooked to perfection. The lobster wasn't rubbery and the seasoning was just right. I originally had my doubts about potato puree, but I found myself wanting an entire bowl of it.
    -The loin of lamb was disappointing. The slices were cut so thin that I didn't feel like I was getting my money's worth. It didn't have much lamb flavor to it either. In fact, all Â I could taste was the sauce that the lamb was dipped in. And where was the mint yogurt? The only sauces I found on my plate was hummus and the eggplant stew.
    -The trio Creme Brulee flavors I got were Bourben, Vanilla & Nutella. Vanilla was my favorite. Distinct vanilla flavor without it being overly sweet.

    Boyfriend:
    -I'm not a fan of cooked oysters, so the Oyster & Caviar wasn't all that great for me.
    -Coconut Thai Curry was pretty good. I was surprised my boyfriend liked it, or even ordered it since he's not a fan of coconut. But he absolutely loved this dish.
    -The seared filet of beef was good. From the bite I had though, the meat seemed to be tougher than i expected it to be.
    -The chocolate souflee was light and fluffy... It felt like a cloud melting in your mouth.

    The waiters were extremely polite. I thought we'd be discriminated against since we were so much younger than everybody else there, but we were still treated with respect & I appreciated that a lot.

    I didn't get full off of the courses though, I ate every single thing off the plate and left glad that I came half hungry and that they had complimentary bread. Maybe our portions were smaller since we ordered four courses? All in all, this place is a great place for a date. Definitely fancier & pricier than the places I'm used to going to as a poor college student. But I'd definitely come back again for a special day.

    9/17/2011

    I have been wanting to go here fora while and finally had the chance when I decided to take my fiance here for his 35th birthday. It lived up the hype, which I think is hard to do!

    I think what really sets this place apart from other nice restaurants is the level of service. The service was brilliant - they were timely, knowledgeable AND they were nice. I cannot stress that last point enough. I have been to some excellent restaurants where the servers were good at their jobs but snooty. You kind of expect that from high-end restaurants but I have to say that I really prefer the approachable and friendly tact that this restaurant has taken.

    I actually liked the atmosphere of the place - muted but soothing decor and the fresh flowers we had near our seat kept giving me some beautiful smells to savor in between meals. We were seated in an intimate corner booth for two, which was perfect for the special occasion (also great for people watching).

    The food was also notable, as you'd expect. I really appreciate the flexibility in the menu. I decided to do a five course meal consisting of 2 apps, 1 seafood dish, a meat dish, and a dessert. They'll adjust the size of each dish regardless of whether it's an app or an entree to make sure you're full by the end - and that definitely seemed to work for me! I was fully satiated by the end.

    I had the fried egg and polenta dish first, which I thought was just delicious. I followed that with the lobster risotto, which was also a big win. Both of these were hearty and had a nice blend of different flavors and textures. I then moved to a coconut seafood curry - that was interesting. It was probably my least favorite dish, although I think most people would probably like it. I just happen to be one of those darn Americans who likes their thai-style food to taste like cheap thai restaurants make it. :-P My meat course was buffalo, which I thought was excellently prepared and tasted very nice. I ended the meal with a selection of sorbets, which I really loved for their flavor - the passion fruit was my particular favorite.

    I'll let my fiance write his own review of his meal if he would like, but I think it's safe to say we both came away very satisfied with the experience, and we would definitely value a return trip.
